# NextGit Project Rules

## Project Overview

NextGit is a Glulx interpreter for the ZX Spectrum Next.

It is based on:
- Git (Glulx interpreter)
- A custom Glk implementation called NextGlk

## Structure

/docs - Documentation
/nextglk - implementation
/tests - tests
/thirdparty - third party code used as references, you don't need to look here unless asked to


## Building

Never use

    make
    make clean

use the scripts in the root of the project 
- rebuild-cheapglk.ps1 builds "gitc" against cheapglk
- rebuild-nextglk.ps1 builds "gitn" against nextglk

cheapglk is just for compatibility checks, our production target is nextglk 


The default Git Makefile configuration still targets CheapGlk.

## Architecture

Game
  -> Git VM
  -> Glk ABI
  -> NextGlk
  -> Spectrum Next platform

Git must remain as close to upstream as possible.

Do not modify Git VM behaviour unless explicitly requested.

Prefer implementing missing functionality in NextGlk.

## Platform

Target:
- ZX Spectrum Next
- z88dk
- NextZXOS
- SD card storage

Optional:
- Raspberry Pi acceleration

The interpreter must function without the Raspberry Pi.

## Glk

NextGlk is a genuine Glk implementation.

Do not create alternative abstraction layers.

Use:
- glk.h
- gi_dispa.c
- gi_dispa.h

as the ABI contract.

## Memory

Do not implement memory banking inside NextGlk.

Memory banking belongs to:
- VM memory manager
- Story memory subsystem

NextGlk owns:
- UI state
- Image cache
- Platform I/O

## Graphics

Games use:
- Inform 7
- Glulx
- Inline images

Current requirements:
- Inline image display
- No sound

Initial UI layout:

+----------------------+
|       IMAGE          |
+----------------------+
|      TEXT            |
|      TEXT            |
| >                    |
+----------------------+

## Coding Rules

Always provide:
- complete files
- complete functions

Never provide:
- partial snippets
- search-and-replace instructions
- "insert here" guidance

When generating code:
- compileable first
- functional later

Stub implementations are acceptable if clearly marked.

## Development Strategy

1. Match Glk ABI.
2. Build compileable stubs.
3. Replace stubs incrementally.
4. Keep commits small.
5. Prefer understanding over implementation.

## Documentation

Before implementing a subsystem:
- identify ABI
- identify ownership
- document architecture

Prefer documentation before code.

